For our final project, we wanted to create a program that was more difficult than our previous one but also included the aspects we liked about Stack. Because of this, we decided to incorporate user input into our project again this time through the form of head tracking. We also chose to use Python to do this as it was newer to us and allowed us to hone our skills beyond just what we learned in class. In the end, we decided to create a 3D world that a user could maneuver through with their head movements. To do this, we first showed a webcam which allowed the user to press C to calibrate their head position when straight and then calculated head position based off their offset from that position. The application then takes the user to the 3D world we created and allows them to move their head up, down, left, right, forwards, and backwards to move similarly through the world. Though this project was very challenging, It taught us a number of skills from using AI coding agents to how to understand new packages and their given functions. 

Through this project, we learned how to convert our more advanced Matlab skills into python through better understanding the syntax differences between the languages. Further, we understood how to implement user camera input rather than just keypresses like in our previous project. We also were able to understand worldbuilding in Python and how to create a detailed graphic world using a complex package without a wrapper. Additionally, we were able to see how Github as a tool transcends coding languages and is used similarly for collaboration regardless of whether we’re coding in Matlab or Python. Using an AI coding agent was also a new skill we gained as balancing our own vision and skills with the efficiency that the Cursor agent provided us was challenging at first. 

The biggest challenge we faced when coding this project was with developing the 3D world. We originally intended to use Ursina which is a wrapper for Panda3D as the functions for Panda3D are not intuitive and include a lot of extra code. Ursina made that easier by simplifying the syntax ont he user’s end and making it more representative of what the functions were actually doing. However, we encountered several issues with the package as our coding environment was not fully compatible with the package no matter which version of Python we downloaded or where we moved the folder. Thus, we transitioned to just using Panda3D where the functions and syntax were much more convoluted. This made it so we had to restart our worldbuilding and also use a program that was much more difficult to understand, however we were able to create a world we were happy with in the end. 

Our biggest triumph was running the final product for the first time. Because we were working towards our head movements moving the 3D world, we were excited to try that out for the first time. Seeing our head movements vaguely influence the movement of the 3D world was satisfying, though we had to continue to tweak it for increased accuracy. 

Finally, our biggest “aha” moment was when we figured out how to implement the arithmetic for the head tracking. Understanding the logic behind the inequalities in relation to the dx, dy, and dz movement allowed us to have the program accurately show direction when our head was moving to that corresponding side. Also, figuring out how to make the labels more accurate for “looking _______” was an aha moment as well. We manipulated the speed, points tracked, sensitivity, etc. until we made it as accurate as possible.

Overall, we really enjoyed building this project and felt that we were able to challenge ourselves. Thank you!!
